WEBVTT



00:00:00.210 --> 00:00:04.230
Welcome my friend to today's
lecture on financial terms.

00:00:04.590 --> 00:00:07.590
Let's decode this concept like detectives

00:00:09.900 --> 00:00:10.860
concept explanation.

00:00:11.985 --> 00:00:17.115
Financial terms, my friend, are the secret
language of the economy and banking.

00:00:17.535 --> 00:00:19.995
Understanding them is your superpower.

00:00:20.445 --> 00:00:25.035
These words describe everything
about money, markets and investments.

00:00:25.365 --> 00:00:28.035
Let's start with the big ones first.

00:00:28.125 --> 00:00:28.935
Inflation.

00:00:29.295 --> 00:00:34.305
This is when the price of everything
from your samosa to your petrol goes

00:00:34.305 --> 00:00:36.975
up and your money's power goes down.

00:00:37.300 --> 00:00:42.010
Basically your a hundred rupe note
feels like it went on a crash Diet.

00:00:42.520 --> 00:00:44.200
Next is deflation.

00:00:44.470 --> 00:00:46.780
It's the complete opposite of inflation.

00:00:47.140 --> 00:00:51.460
Prices are falling and suddenly
your money feels like a bodybuilder.

00:00:51.730 --> 00:00:52.870
It can buy more.

00:00:53.260 --> 00:00:58.360
While this sounds fantastic, prolonged
deflation can be a real party pooper for

00:00:58.360 --> 00:01:01.180
the economy as it discourages spending.

00:01:01.625 --> 00:01:03.365
Then we have the repo rate.

00:01:03.785 --> 00:01:08.405
This is the interest rate at which our
big boss, the Reserve Bank of India,

00:01:08.495 --> 00:01:10.505
lends money to commercial banks.

00:01:10.925 --> 00:01:14.825
Think of the RBI as the
ultimate money lender for banks.

00:01:15.125 --> 00:01:18.035
It's a key tool to
control the money supply.

00:01:18.425 --> 00:01:20.735
The opposite is the reverse repo rate.

00:01:21.095 --> 00:01:24.125
This is the rate at which
the RBI borrows money.

00:01:24.325 --> 00:01:28.105
From the commercial banks, when
banks have too much cash lying

00:01:28.105 --> 00:01:32.095
around, they can pocket it with
the RBI and earn some interest.

00:01:32.455 --> 00:01:35.485
This helps suck out extra
money from the system.

00:01:35.995 --> 00:01:42.835
Now, the cash reserve ratio or CRR, this
is a specific percentage of a bank's total

00:01:42.835 --> 00:01:45.655
deposits that it must keep with the RBI.

00:01:46.075 --> 00:01:48.745
This is the look, but don't touch money.

00:01:48.955 --> 00:01:50.725
Banks can't use it for lending.

00:01:51.390 --> 00:01:56.220
Similar, but different is the
statutory liquidity ratio or SLR.

00:01:56.580 --> 00:02:01.290
This is also a percentage of a bank's
deposits, but the bank gets to keep this

00:02:01.290 --> 00:02:07.320
money with itself in the form of liquid
assets like cash gold or government bonds.

00:02:07.695 --> 00:02:11.415
We often hear about gross
domestic product or GDP.

00:02:11.805 --> 00:02:16.665
This is the total value of all finished
goods and services made within a

00:02:16.665 --> 00:02:19.005
country's borders in a specific time.

00:02:19.275 --> 00:02:23.415
It's like the country's annual report
card showing its economic health.

00:02:23.925 --> 00:02:28.815
A term that gives bankers nightmares
is non-performing asset, or NPA.

00:02:29.265 --> 00:02:32.745
An NPA is a loan where the
borrower has stopped paying the

00:02:32.745 --> 00:02:35.265
principal or interest for 90 days.

00:02:35.555 --> 00:02:40.565
It's the loan that went on a vacation
and forgot to come back to pay its bills.

00:02:41.045 --> 00:02:44.165
Fiscal policy is about the
government's own wallet.

00:02:44.525 --> 00:02:49.565
It refers to the government's decisions on
its spending and how much tax it collects.

00:02:49.895 --> 00:02:51.755
It's used to steer the economy.

00:02:52.145 --> 00:02:53.885
And finally, monetary policy.

00:02:54.610 --> 00:02:58.420
This refers to the actions of
a central bank like our RBI

00:02:58.570 --> 00:03:00.280
to manage money and credit.

00:03:00.670 --> 00:03:03.670
This is the RBI playing
DJ with the economy.

00:03:03.940 --> 00:03:09.430
Using tools like interest rates, CRR
and SLR to get the rhythm just right.

00:03:11.710 --> 00:03:13.120
Real world relevance.

00:03:13.725 --> 00:03:14.925
Why should you care?

00:03:15.315 --> 00:03:19.605
Well, understanding these terms
directly impacts decision making In

00:03:19.605 --> 00:03:24.435
banking, for instance, inflation helps
in figuring out the real value of

00:03:24.435 --> 00:03:26.685
money and influences lending rates.

00:03:27.045 --> 00:03:31.815
The repo rate directly affects how much
it costs banks to get funds, which then

00:03:31.815 --> 00:03:33.760
decides the interest rates on your loans.

00:03:34.455 --> 00:03:38.385
The cash reserve ratio determines
how much money banks have to lend

00:03:38.385 --> 00:03:40.695
out affecting credit in the economy.

00:03:41.055 --> 00:03:45.525
Managing non-performing assets is the
core banking function for survival.

00:03:45.945 --> 00:03:50.355
The gross domestic product gives a big
picture view of the economy, helping

00:03:50.355 --> 00:03:55.185
banks plan for the future, and fiscal
policy impacts government borrowing,

00:03:55.275 --> 00:03:57.465
which can influence the entire market.

